snippet.textDisplay: At Amy K. about the Coronavirus 2:22:48 : Scientists can make the vaccine. In fact, according to Nature the trials will start at the end of April (https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-00555-x). Although I am sure there are brilliant students in SC, knowledge isn't the issue and therefore, in this specific instance, education isn't the problem. It takes the FDA an absurd amount of time and accrues an absurd cost for the drug development process and then the drug companies charge high amounts for the vaccine once it is developed. After all of these factors you also have many people without access to a primary healthcare provider ("PCP") -- or even those with health insurance who choose to not keep a working relationship with their PCP. The drug industry as a whole including the requirements placed on it by the FDA should be reviewed for their efficacy and emergency situations may warrant an expedited drug development process because a year of testing is too long when people are dying. The primary issue is having leadership in the drug development sphere who try to balance the scientific process with the ethical implications of taking too long.
